<TEXT>
the outcome was left 
hanging monday in a presidential election in which incumbent 
joaquin balaguer was leading by less than 1 percent of the vote 
leftist challenger juan bosch accused conservative balaguer of 
fraud and said sunday that balaguer supporters were paying 40 for 
voterregistration cards in strongholds of boschs dominican 
liberation party 
but some observers believe that bosch 80 a former president 
overthrown by a military coup in 1963 may have lost the election 
through campaign blunders to his 83yearold rival and the 
countrys fivetime president 
after tabulating votes for five days the central electoral 
board said sunday it was suspending further announcements of the 
count on recommendation of former president jimmy carter one of 30 
international observers 
electoral board president froilan tavares made no mention of 
possible fraud saying only that officials found errors by some 
polling stations in compiling tally sheets 
tavares said the count would be suspended pending a review of 
tally sheets in the presence of six international observers a 
laborious process that could take days 
the final bulletin issued by the electoral board on saturday 
gave balaguer an 18227vote lead over bosch but late monday his 
unofficial lead had grown to 21970 votes according to the board 
contacted by the associated press 
with 6645 of the 6663 polling stations reporting or 98 
percent balaguer had 667039 votes and bosch 645069 jose 
francisco pena gomez a former socialist mayor of santo domingo 
was third with 442598 according to the board 
after bosch lost an early lead he accused balaguer of 
colossal fraud and threatened street protests but called off 
the protests friday after the electoral board agreed to review 
tally sheets 
before the election bosch said that balaguers social christian 
reformist party prepared 300000 phony votes to rig the election 
balaguer denied it 
the estimated 40 percent turnout from about 32 registered 
voters was the lowest in more than 25 years 
balaguer has remained out of public view since wednesdays 
elections he was said to be in mourning for his sister laita 85 
who died last week 
carter said friday that no candidate had presented evidence of 
fraud but a review of tally sheets would establish whether fraud 
or honest errors had been committed 
balaguer who is blind with glaucoma appeared to be in trouble 
before the election because of this caribbean island nations 
economic crisis a 2 billion construction project was popular 
among the poor but fueled 50percent inflation 
but bosch confused many dominicans two weeks before the election 
by saying a 1954 agreement with the vatican providing that all army 
chaplains be roman catholic should be shelved in history 
museums 
the statement was widely viewed as antichurch in the 
overwhelmingly catholic nation and seemed to support balaguers 
characterization of bosch as a dangerous marxist 
bosch may also have been hurt by saying he would deport back to 
cuba juan jose arteaga a cuban exile who is balaguers chief 
economic adviser 
