<TEXT>
archbishop rembert weakland says some of the 
reasons women choose to have abortions can be reconciled by the 
church without jeopardizing strict roman catholic teaching against 
abortion 
yes there are possibilities there one could reconcile their 
stance with a church position i think that is a possibility 
thats why you have to talk with each one weakland said in an 
interview published monday by the milwaukee sentinel 
weakland said there are various definitions of prochoice 
opinion ranging from abortion on demand to abortion for specific 
reasons and some personal decisions to have abortions might be 
reconciled by the church but that would be on a casebycase 
basis he emphasized 
i would have to see each one he added i dont know that 
i would want to draw a line each time as if outside this line you 
are not in the catholic church i think that is very dangerous 
weaklands comments came just seven months after the national 
conference of catholic bishops the churchs main governing body 
in the united states issued a statement that no catholic can 
responsibly take a prochoice stand 
because he didnt address specific circumstances it was unclear 
how much weaklands position differed from that of other church 
leaders many catholic theologians have said abortions in some 
cases may be permitted to save the life of the mother 
the milwaukee archbishops statement drew an immediate angry 
response from one antiabortion group that recommended he be 
censured by the vatican 
i think he should stop dialoging and start teaching the 
churchs position and why abortion is always wrong and asks his 
priests to do the same from their pulpits said mary dietrich 
secretary of the milwaukee chapter of wisconsin right to life inc 
but frances kissling national president of the washingtonbased 
prochoice group catholics for a free choice praised weaklands 
statements as a real breakthrough 
i goes much further in acknowledging the political arena than 
any other bishop has done to date ms kissling said it gives 
a lot of hope to catholic politicians who have only been hearing 
criticism 
weakland over the weekend issued a 21page statement on his 
findings on womens view of abortions based on several 
informationgathering meetings he had at churches in his diocese 
earlier this year 
greg bell communications director for the milwaukee 
archdiocese said the archbishop was meeting with priests monday 
and couldnt be interviewed but he said weakland didnt intend to 
work against the churchs antiabortion stand or the statement made 
by his us colleagues in november 
he doesnt want to juxtapose himself against the other 
bishops he said hes not calling for redefinition of church 
teaching what he is calling for is for the church to look more 
closely at the root causes of why women choose abortions 
bell said their may be instances in which weakland believes 
the church could understand why a women would have an abortion 
such as when such a womans life is jeopardized 
in the newspaper interview weakland acknowledged his position 
was a bit aggressive but added he did not fear any reprimand 
from the vatican 
