<TEXT>
the commander of us forces in the 
pacific said tuesday he was optimistic us and philippine 
officials would reach a new agreement providing for continued 
american military presence in the philippines 
last friday american and philippine negotiators agreed to hold 
further talks at an unspecified date on whether to renew a lease on 
clark air base subic bay naval base and four smaller installations 
that expires in september 1991 
rafael alunan spokesman for the philippine panel said the next 
round could begin in three to four weeks 
i am very optimistic that we will reach an agreement with 
continued presence in the philippines adm huntington hardisty 
told reporters after meeting foreign secretary raul manglapus 
chief philippine negotiator in the bases talks 
hardisty also said philippine proposals for joint usfilipino 
use of the bases was very feasible the six bases are nominally 
under philippine command but effectively run by the americans 
the united states maintains about 40000 troops defense 
department civilians and military dependents in the philippines 
asked whether the united states would accept a reduced presence 
under a new agreement hardisty said i think well have a 
reduced presence worldwide because of whats happening in europe 
and whats happening worldwide with our defense budget but i also 
think well maintain our forward presence 
on monday hardisty met with president corazon aquino and 
discussed the strategic relationship 
from my personal opinion i think our government feels very 
comfortable with the recent exploratory talks hardisty said 
after the meeting i think both agree that our future depends on 
a new relationship a new strategic relationship 
hardisty was in manila to attend a regular meeting of the 
usphilippine mutual defense board 
after five days of talks last week both sides agreed to 
continue discussions despite differences including manilas claim 
that washington has failed to honor previous commitments on the 
bases 
mrs aquino refuses to say whether she will support a new 
agreement opposition to the bases is growing because many 
filipinos view them as an infringement on national sovereignty 
on may 13 on the eve of the talks communist rebels opposed to 
the bases killed two us airmen near clark air base 
on monday philippine police said the rebels also had planned to 
assassinate senior us military officers but the plots were foiled 
when police began searching suspected rebel hideouts for the 
killers of the two servicemen 
on friday the pentagon announced american diplomats and service 
members in the philippines would receive hazardous duty pay because 
of the communist threat 
on tuesday police defused bombs outside the headquarters of two 
banks in the financial district in manila officials said the bombs 
could have destroyed both buildings had they exploded 
in another incident assailants hurled three grenades at two 
branches of the security branch and trust co one of the banks 
where the bombs were found there were no injuries and only minor 
damage in the attacks police said 
police said they did not know who was responsible for the bombs 
but the explosives were the same kind used by military mutineers in 
decembers coup attempt 
