<TEXT>
more than 200 scientists asked the chinese 
government monday to allow dissidents fang lizhi and his wife li 
shuxian to leave china and threatened to boycott scientific 
conferences there until the human rights activists were free to 
emigrate 
the scientists led by soviet physicist yuri orlov also urged 
the us government to put more pressure on china to permit the 
fangs to leave their refuge at the american embassy without threat 
of arrest 
the chinese government accused fang an astrophysicist and human 
rights activist of inciting the may 1989 prodemocracy 
demonstrations in beijings tiananmen square he and li also a 
scientist fled to the us embassy 
the two have refused to sign an admission of guilt for 
responsibility for the demonstrations which ended in a bloody 
crackdown and martial law 
we should try to push the opportunistic and insensitive us 
administration in the right direction orlov told a news 
conference 
president bush must decide by june 3 whether to extend most 
favored nation trading status to china the administration is under 
pressure from congressional democrats and human rights activists to 
deny the trading preference because of chinas crackdown on 
prodemocracy demonstrations last year 
officials who asked not to be identified said monday bush had 
decided to extend the favored trade status for another year 
the appeal includes petitions signed by 224 prominent 
scientists including several nobel laureates to the chinese 
government through its academy of sciences and to secretary of 
state james a baker iii urging freedom for fang and li 
as scientists dedicated to the truth and free inquiry we 
cannot remain silent while our colleagues in the peoples republic 
of china are held captive because of their pursuit of these 
ideals the petitions said 
the scientists also said they would encourage boycotts of 
scientific conferences in china until the fangs are released aryeh 
neier executive director of human rights watch said 11 such 
conferences were scheduled between may and september in china 
robert l park chairman of the american physical society said 
discussions for new scientific conferences will not take place as 
martial law persists and peaceful dissent is suppressed 
fangs son fang ke a graduate physics student at wayne state 
university said he has been in touch with his parents by mail 
they have a good spirit the kind of spirit chinese people have 
especially of their generation he said 
