<TEXT>
india is moving tens of thousands of 
battleready soldiers to its border with pakistan prompting fear 
among western diplomats of another war over kashmir 
western military experts say india also is seeking to buy large 
quantities of movable bridges troop transport boats and other 
equipment that could be used in an attack 
in addition the government recently formed a paramilitary unit 
called the national rifles which could undertake counterinsurgency 
operations in the troubled state of jammukashmir freeing the army 
to go to the border 
interviews with military experts from the west and asia 
indicated several countries were seriously considering the 
possibility of war between india and pakistan one western officer 
said his embassy was discussing contingency plans for withdraal of 
embassy personnel and their families 
a month ago many of the same officers said war was impossible 
weve changed our assessment a highranking western officer 
said we think there now is a 5050 chance 
experts say the developments are doubly disturbing because both 
countries are believed to possess nuclear weapons technology india 
exploded a nuclear device in 1974 
both also have mediumrange missiles 
the focus of the problem is jammukashmir the only indian state 
with a moslem majority 
both nations claim the scenic region of valleys and himalayan 
mountains and have fought two wars over it since winning 
independence from britain in 1947 
nearly 400 people have been killed in jammukashmir since the 
indian government began a crackdown on moslem separatists jan 20 
india accuses pakistan of arming the insurgents and training 
them in camps across the border pakistan claims to provide only 
moral support 
western military officers said several developments contributed 
to their changed attitude about the possibility of war 
rhetoric has grown hotter on both sides 
in april prime minister vp singh of india told his countrymen 
to be psychologically prepared for war rightwing groups in 
india have called for limited military strikes into pakistan 
pakistans prime minister benazir bhutto has told the kashmiri 
separatists your blood is our blood 
both countries especially india appear to be backing up their 
words with action 
india has undertaken a slow but steady buildup of forces 
along its entire border with pakistan military experts say 
in the last month the 57th and 8th divisions totaling about 
20000 men were moved from the northeast frontier with china to 
kashmir according to two western experts like the others they 
spoke on condition of anonymity 
military officers said india would not have shifted troops from 
one sensitive region to another without an express purpose 
india lost a war with china in 1962 although tensions have 
eased between the countries new delhi still regards beijing as a 
threat 
western experts say deployment of the paramilitary national 
rifles commanded by an army lieutenant general will allow army 
troops in the kashmir valley take positions along the border both 
in kashmir and farther south 
they say india is strengthening its border forces in rajasthan 
and punjab states on the flat plain that stretches into the heart 
of pakistan 
the pakistanis appear to have done less actual preparation for 
war but have put border regions on alert the western experts say 
they found it highly disturbing that pakistan had followed 
regularly scheduled battlefield exercises with another series 
during the next few months the experts said they believe india 
will try to seal the kashmir front to prevent moslem militants from 
sneaking through the high mountain passes when the snow melts 
they will crack down hard in the valley during the hot 
summer and the rainy season one officer said 
if the separatist struggle continues in september western 
officers say india might be tempted to launch an air strike at the 
alleged training camps in pakistan 
they said india probably would seek to maintain the status quo 
in kashmir against pakistani retaliation and attack on the ground 
from rajasthan or punjab 
indias goal would be to seize as much territory as possible 
before negotiations began they said 
a governmentfinanced think tank has come out in favor of 
limited strikes against pakistan 
the institute for defense studies and analyses citing western 
precedents said in its latest paper india has every right to 
retaliate against the bases of terrorism and the country that 
sponsors the terrorism 
but one good sign for peace is that many in the indian military 
do not appear to want a war 
the army has just finished a difficult 30month peacekeeping 
operation in sri lanka where it lost more than 1100 men to 
attacks by tamil guerrillas indian officers have been quoted as 
saying their economically strapped nation cannot afford a war 
which would cost an estimated 47 million a day 
