<TEXT>
politics lobbying and public opinion polls 
drive congress agenda but sometimes another motivation comes into 
play personal tragedy 
such is the case with two house bills debated this month one 
on family leave policy and the other aimed at expanding the rights 
of the disabled 
republican rep marge roukema of new jersey has spent a decade 
in the house racking up a probusiness voting record but on the 
issue of whether the government should give employees the right to 
unpaid leave for family medical emergencies she and the business 
lobby part ways 
roukema was the prime republican sponsor of the bill which 
passed the house earlier this month she scolded those especially 
business groups who went the other way 
the organized business lobby in washington is out of step with 
the real world and that includes conscientious nononsense 
bottomline business people at the grass roots she said the 
lobbyists have overreacted in a way that no one can explain to me 
for mrs roukema the need to take unpaid leave from work to 
care for a new child or a critically ill relative relates directly 
to her own suffering 
these are not abstract problems she told the house in an 
emotional speech i know ive been there 
she recalled that when she started raising a family her son was 
stricken with fatal leukemia he needed home care i was free to 
remain at home and give him the loving care he needed but today 
many households dont have the luxury of one spouse making enough 
money so the other can quit work 
i continually asked myself during this process what would i 
have done if i not only had the tragedy and the trauma of caring 
for my child but also had to worry about losing a job and a roof 
over my head she said 
many years later mrs roukema found an answer in the parental 
leave bill 
this week the house expected to complete action on the 
