yehuda lisky editor of the last yiddish newspaper 
in britain is dead at 90 the daily telegraph reported today 
the newspaper described lisky as a champion of yiddish culture 
who wrote yiddish spoke yiddish dreamed yiddish and as he once 
put it drank yiddish although in fact his favorite drink was 
scotch 
from his own resources in the 1950s lisky launched dos yiddishe 
folk the jewish people it was published first weekly then 
biweekly then monthly and finally whenever he had the money and 
energy to produce it he launched the newspaper in collaboration 
with avron stencl the poet of londons east end 
yiddish was the common language of east european jewry it 
largely disappeared following the nazi persecution of world war ii 
and the dying out of the older generation of survivors 
lisky was born in oszene poland and joined his brother abraham 
fuchs an established yiddish writer living in vienna 
he came to london in 1930 and worked on a yiddish daily die 
zeit when it folded in 1950 lisky started his own paper he also 
taught yiddish at summer and winter schools in oxford 
lisky was short in stature bespectacled and cheerful he wore a 
black beret pulled low over his right ear and was wellknown around 
the cafes and bookstores of east and central london he lost the 
sight of one eye when he was attacked by a robber in his london 
home in his 90th year 
the daily telegraph said liskys wife sonia died in 1984 and 
they are survived by two sons 
it did not give the date or cause of death 
