<TEXT>
exxon has begun applying fertilizer to 
the shoreline to speed the breakdown of oil from the exxon valdez 
spill 
the company got the goahead from the state to use the chemicals 
after a debate over whether they would cause even more harm to the 
environment 
our key objective is to achieve the appropriate level of 
cleanup with the least amount of stress on the environment said 
bob mastracchio exxons technical manager for the cleanup 
this years cleanup got under way may 1 with crews removing tar 
by hand exxon expects to complete its work by midaugust under a 
cleanup plan approved by the governments cleanup coordinator said 
exxon spokesman joe tucker 
the exxon valdez ran aground on a reef on march 24 1989 
spilling nearly 11 million gallons of crude oil into the clear 
waters of prince william sound 
after the spill thousands of cleanup workers and hundreds of 
boats worked for weeks to clean hundreds of miles of shoreline 
thousands of birds mammals and other wildlife were killed in the 
nations worst oil spill 
late sunday workers began spreading nitrogen and phosphorous 
fertilizer in liquid and granular form the chemicals promote the 
growth of bacteria that eat oil 
three boats and 29 people were deployed to coat about 175 square 
yards tucker said only three three or four workers were actually 
applying the fertilizer most of the rest were federal state or 
company officials observing the work 
to protect birds and other wildlife from the potentially harmful 
chemicals crews put out brightlycolored helium balloons and roped 
off the treated areas with flags 
the cleansing action of the tides will reduce the risk after the 
first 24 hours exxon said 
the company plans to use the fertilizer on about 400 sites last 
year 74 miles of shoreline were treated 
a multiagency team will monitor the sites for six weeks to help 
judge the effectiveness of the technique bioremediation and 
decide whether second applications of the fertilizer will be made 
during the summer exxon said 
state officials and some environmental groups have expressed 
fears that the chemicals might further pollute the water or harm 
wildlife 
after weeks of debate the state finally agreed with exxon and 
the coast guard that the technique should be used despite the risks 
</TEXT>
