<TEXT>
the supreme court today upheld a law requiring 
people convicted of federal crimes to pay money into a fund to help 
crime victims 
the court unanimously rejected arguments that the law is 
unconstitutional because it originated in the senate and not in 
the house of representatives 
the constitution states that all revenueraising bills shall 
originate in the house of representatives but the court relying 
on an 1897 decision today said the victims of crime act of 1984 is 
not a revenueraising measure 
the law is aimed at generating money to offset the costs of 
helping crime victims by imposing special assessments against 
convicted criminals 
justice thurgood marshall invoked the 1897 decision in stating 
a statute that creates a particular governmental program and that 
raises revenue to suppport that program as opposed to a statute 
that raises revenue to support government generally is not a bill 
for raising revenue within the meaning of the constitutions 
origination clause 
the case stemmed from a 50 assessment against a man named 
german munozflores who was convicted of helping an illegal alien 
evade inspection by immigration officials in san diego county 
calif five years ago 
munozflores was placed on probation for two years 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals overturned the assessment 
agreeing with arguments that the law was a revenueraising measure 
enacted improperly by congress 
todays decision reversed the 9th circuit courts ruling 
the ruling is a victory for the bush administration even though 
the justices rejected its argument that the case presented a 
political question federal courts should avoid 
the government may be right that a judicial finding that 
congress has passed an unconstitutional law might in some sense be 
said to entail a lack of respect for congress judgment marshall 
said 
but disrespect in the sense the government uses the term 
cannot be sufficient to create a political question he said 
if it were every judicial resolution of a constitutional 
challenge to a congressional enactment would be impermissible 
the case is us vs munozflores 881932 
</TEXT>
