<TEXT>
states may impose labeling and reporting 
requirements on liquor sold at us military bases within their 
borders the supreme court ruled today 
the court said north dakotas regulation of liquor sold at two 
military bases there does not violate a clause of the constitution 
which generally gives federal policy priority over state 
regulations 
north dakota requires that all liquor sold in the state be 
distributed through a statecontrolled system 
the state said outofstate liquor distributors must put a label 
on each bottle sold at the grand forks and minot air force bases 
stating that the liquor is for consumption only at the military 
installations 
the state also said suppliers must report monthly on how much 
liquor they shipped into the state 
the high court upheld the labeling regulation by a 54 vote and 
the reporting rule 90 
justice john paul stevens in the courts main opinion said 
both regulations are valid under the 21st amendment to the 
constitution which repealed prohibition and gave states sweeping 
power over liquor distribution 
stevens said the rules serve the states legitimate interest in 
preventing diversion of liquor from military bases into the 
civilian market 
he was joined by chief justice william h rehnquist and justices 
byron r white and sandra day oconnor 
justice antonin scalia voted to uphold both regulations but for 
different reasons he expressed in a separate concurring opinion 
voting to uphold north dakotas reporting regulation but strike 
down the labeling requirement were justices william j brennan 
thurgood marshall harry a blackmun and anthony m kennedy 
federal officials challenged north dakotas liquor regulation 
system on grounds it violates a federal policy aimed at assuring 
liquor sold at clubs and stores on military bases would be purchaed 
by the government at the lowest possible price profits from the 
military base sales are used to pay for recreational activities 
federal officials said it could cost the government 200000 to 
250000 more each year if they are forced to abide by north 
dakotas rules 
they said the regulations will force them to purchase more 
liquor from north dakota distributors at higher prices 
todays ruling overturns a 1988 decision by the 8th us circuit 
court of appeals 
the national beer wholesalers association supported north 
dakotas appeal saying the state has good reason to be concerned 
about diversion of liquor from military bases 
the case is north dakota vs us 88926 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
