<TEXT>
two championship caliber golf courses in 
scottsdale ariz produce revenues for the city local business 
and the professional golf tour leaving only the landowner without 
a dime 
the landlord is the federal government 
the interior departments bureau of reclamation had the option 
of investing money to help turn a desert into golf courses and 
cutting itself in on subsequent revenues 
the bureau chose not to invest instead simply leasing the land 
free to the city 
scottsdale then built the courses and hired a subsidiary of the 
profitmaking pga tour to run them the city gets a percentage of 
the course fees and sales the pga makes a profit the us 
government which has the land as a flood control project gets 
nothing 
the deal doesnt look like a hole in one to rep mike synar 
dokla whose house government operations environment subcommittee 
is investigating the arrangement and plans to hold a hearing this 
summer 
it begs the question of whether they had any common sense and 
whether they had any vision synar said of the federal lease 
negotiators if people in the private sector did these kind of 
deals theyd be fired 
bureau of reclamation officials said their purpose was to turn 
the area into a public recreation project and avoid maintenance 
costs 
if we had to do it again we would look at the revenue issue a 
lot more in depth said bob michaels a bureau recreational 
resource specialist in phoenix who helped negotiate the lease 
city officials had a similar purpose in avoiding maintenance 
costs but still arranged to benefit from course revenues and 
their vision didnt stop with the golf courses 
scottsdale allowed a resort the princess to be built next door 
on nonfederal land the citys room tax on the resort brings in 
additional revenue the princess also generates business for the 
courses 17 percent of the tee times are reserved for its guests 
