<TEXT>
urban educators concerned that their students 
will be overlooked in a national effort to improve education formed 
a task force monday aimed specifically at problems facing big city 
schools 
over the last five years numerous reports have been written 
about the condition of urban education in this country said 
joseph fernandez chancellor of new york city schools 
while many of these reports contain excellent recommendations 
it is critical that the practitioners those impacted most by the 
recommendations become involved in discussions of our national 
education agenda fernandez said 
holmes braddock presidentelect of the council of the great 
city schools said the task force would develop its plan within 
three years 
urban schools he said have heavy concentrations of minorities 
or nonenglish speaking children as well as lowachievers and 
lowincome students other problems include crumbling facilities 
and inadequate teaching materials 
fernandez will head the group which will analyze goals that 
include increasing expectations for all urban school students and 
adequately staffing urban schools with qualified teachers who are 
culturally and racially sensitive and who reflect the racial 
characteristics of their students 
the task force also will review ways to restructure education in 
urban areas and discuss controversial ideas such as eliminating 
grading and testing from kindergarten through third grade 
lengthening school days team teaching and increased federal 
financial commitment 
fernandez said the task force would seek bottom up 
approaches as opposed to the top down scenario offered by the 
nations governors a final report on the urban goals will be 
completed by jan 15 1991 
the national education goals approved by president bush and the 
governors in february are targeted for 2000 
those goals say all children will start school ready to learn 
high school graduation rates will increase to at least 90 percent 
american students will be first in the world in mathematics and 
science students will leave grades four eight and 12 competent in 
basic subjects every american adult will be literate and every 
school free of violence and drugs 
the council of the great city schools is a coalition of 45 of 
the nations largest urban school districts 
</TEXT>
