military officers in el salvador have risen to 
power despite having commanded units linked to human rights abuses 
according to a report issued monday on the eve of a congressional 
battle over cutting us military aid 
the congressional study said 14 of the countrys 15 senior 
military commanders have commanded units that are documented to 
have killed civilians tortured prisoners carried out kidnappings 
or covered up such abuses 
the promotion to senior positions of so many officers whose 
troops committed repeated abuses of human rights and the absence 
of prosecutions of even junior officers for these abuses suggest 
that at a basic level there is little accountability concluded 
the report by the arms control and foreign policy caucus 
the report underscoring the already tarnished reputation of the 
salvadoran military was issued the day before a partisan house 
floor battle over us military aid to el salvador the aid totals 
85 million this year and the bush administration wants the same 
level for the fiscal year that begins oct 1 
but some democrats claim they will narrowly win a vote to slash 
the military aid in half this year and next and to impose 
conditions to pressure the government and leftist rebels to reach a 
negotiated peacemoved 
