<TEXT>
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev is 
sending arms experts here later in the week to resume presummit 
negotiations to cut longrange nuclear weapons and they will find 
the bush administration in a mood to strike a deal 
the negotiators will take up a halfdozen issues that were not 
resolved by secretary of state james a baker iii last week in 
moscow the aim is to settle as many as they can before gorbachev 
arrives may 30 for summit talks with president bush 
the us strategy is to look for a tradeoff accepting the 
position taken by the soviets on some issues in exchange for their 
agreeing to the us stand on others a senior us official said 
monday he spoke on condition of anonymity 
the bush administration is not tipping its hand about its 
priorities before the talks begin wednesday or thursday at the 
state department but one of the main us objectives is to keep 
the soviets from improving their powerful ss18 nuclear missiles 
as part of the strategic arms reduction treaty the soviets 
already have agreed to reduce their arsenal of 308 of these 
landbased intercontinental ballistic missiles by 50 percent to 
154 
the bush administration would like to halt improvements in the 
missiles that will remain but is reluctant to accept curbs on its 
own arsenal of deadly multiwarhead ballistic missiles carried 
aboard nuclear submarines 
other unsettled issues include how many landbased mobile 
missiles would be allowed whether the soviet backfire bomber 
should be regulated and how to verify compliance with a start 
treaty 
another tough issue restricting nucleartipped cruise missiles 
was resolved during the four days of talks baker held in moscow 
that breakthrough involved a tradeoff baker accepted the range 
limitations proposed by the soviets on cruise missiles carried 
aboard airplanes while the soviets agreed to exclude the new us 
tacit rainbow airtosurface missile from any restraints 
also the soviets gave in to the us demand that there be no 
inspection of cruise missiles carried aboard submarines 
bakers trip also produced what he called a trailblazing 
ussoviet agreement to end the production of chemical weapons 
but with the summit only 10 days away the two sides are 
concentrating on trying to reach agreement on as many strategic 
weapons reductions as they can include in a declaration to be 
initialed by bush and gorbachev 
the soviet delegation will be headed by aleksander bessmertnykh 
a close adviser to gorbachev he is due to present his credentials 
to bush next monday as the new soviet ambassador under secretary 
of state reginald bartholomew will head the us team 
meanwhile us and soviet negotiators are continuing to work on 
the treaty in geneva the proposed text runs 400 to 500 pages even 
if all key issues are settled it will take several months at 
least to complete it 
work in vienna on another treaty to cut us and soviet troops 
tanks artillery airplanes and helicopters in europe has slowed 
down baker was unable to perk up the negotiations during his 
meetings in moscow with gorbachev and foreign minister eduard a 
shevardnadze 
the soviets are reluctant to pull 600000 soldiers out of 
central europe until they are assured the german army also will be 
sharply reduced 
even so the bush administration intends to go as far as it can 
in completing the start treaty 
richard boucher a state department spokesman said monday the 
administration would not delay completing one accord while the 
other lagged start can be a very important agreement he said 
the treaty would cut us and soviet strategic nuclear weapons 
by 30 percent to 35 percent overall 
