<TEXT>
david wood a journalist who reported life at the 
top of british politics with deep knowledge and insight for the 
times of london has died at 75 his former newspaper reported 
monday 
wood died friday according to the newspaper the cause of death 
was not disclosed 
his bestremembered exclusive was his disclosure on june 1 
1959 that foreign secretary selwyn lloyd had been told by prime 
minister harold macmillan that enough was enough and he would 
be transferred to another cabinet post in several months time 
the report created an international sensation because lloyd was 
then in geneva attending a presummit conference of the prime 
ministers of the socalled big four nations british french 
soviet and us and his position was undermined 
lloyd was a controversial figure because he had been foreign 
secretary during the anglofrench secret collusion with israel and 
invasion of egypt over the suez crisis in 1956 
macmillan and government information officers denied woods 
report on lloyd but it was macmillan himself who had given wood 
the information lloyd was made chancellor of the exchequer the 
following year 
later when top officials of the conservative party were 
discussing who would succeed macmillan wood reported accurately 
what was going on and ranking tories tried to have him thrown out 
of his job they were rebuffed by the late sir william haley who 
is remembered as one of the great editors of the 205yearold 
newspaper 
wood a laborers son became a reporter in his hometown of 
grantham when he was 14 he was a fast shorthand writer and in 
reporting the town council he got to know alderman alfred roberts 
whose daughter margaret is today prime minister thatcher 
in world war ii wood served in tanks in north africa and was an 
intelligence officer in france and germany he joined the times in 
1948 and was its political editor for more than 20 years 
his monday morning articles on the background of politics were 
essential reading for all legislators and notable for the fine 
quality of writing and their political insight the times obituary 
said 
wood retired in 1979 
he is survived by a son and a daughter 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

