<TEXT>
latin america will gain a place of first 
importance in us foreign policy as the cold war ebbs deputy 
secretary of state lawrence eagleburger said monday 
eagleburgers statement delivered before an audience of 
corporate executives was clearly intended to reassure latin 
american leaders worried that their region will get scant attention 
in the growing us fascination with the collapse of communism in 
eastern europe 
the focus of us policy will increasingly and inevitably be 
drawn to our own hemisphere as relations with the soviet union 
improve and democracy becomes rooted in the former soviet bloc 
eagleburger said 
we may well be at the edge of removing from the us foreign 
policy agenda the tremendous concern with eastwest relations that 
has of necessity dominated the agenda for the last 45 years he 
said 
the world is clearly changing eagleburger said adding that 
the changes will clearly redound to the benefit of latin 
america 
eagleburger said it was natural for the united states to expend 
considerable energy in europe because the prospect of ending the 
cold war is of overriding stategic importance 
but he said longterm responsibility for aiding the nations of 
eastern europe in their struggle to install democratic institutions 
and revive prosperity will be borne by their west european 
neighbors 
success in ending the eastwest struggle and fostering stability 
and prosperity in europe will open a new chapter in us foreign 
policy he said 
the ending of the cold war should bring with it a 
demilitarization of foreign policy and a new set of economic and 
political challenges especially in latin america eagleburger said 
as a result of improvements in eastwest relations latin 
america is going to occupy a place of first importance in us 
foreign policy he said 
us trade with latin america will be seen as a vital national 
interest in part to promote democracy prosperity and stability 
and in part out of sheer selfinterest he said 
but it is an interest that will be increasingly threatened if 
the region remains mired in debt and unable to buy our products 
eagleburger said 
it is clear he said the united states and latin america will 
have to move to open up trade to boost us investment and the 
flow of technology and to help solve latin americas crushing debt 
problems 
statist and protectionist policies must be fully rolled 
back he said if the door is not opened wide enough 
investment will go elsewhere 
eagleburger also predicted the united states will take a a 
much more open attitude toward freetrade agreements but 
acknowleged that negotiating them country by country will be time 
consuming and difficult 
</TEXT>
