<TEXT>
a former us diplomat said monday that he 
gave indonesian military authorities the names of highranking 
communists who were subsequently killed in a 1965 purge that 
terrorized the country 
robert j martens who was a political officer at the us 
embassy in jakarta said he gleaned the names of thousands of 
partai kommunis indonesia or pki activists from the media 
the same reports were available to indonesian authorities but 
martens said the officials were disorganized and didnt appear to 
have the names 
pki with 35 million members and as many as 18 million people 
affiliated with it was the largest communist party in the world 
and was active in every level of government and the military 
martens now an adviser to the state department said the pki 
was in danger of taking control of indonesia at a time when 
communists were flexing their muscle throughout asia 
the purge of the pki at the end of 1965 coincided with the start 
of us activity against the communists in vietnam 
among the names he provided were all the members of the pkis 
central committee martens said in an interview 
i thought it was the right thing to do he said i have no 
regrets 
martens said he gave names of activists in the cities and within 
the party apparatus and not in the provinces martens said he and 
other us officials were aware that indonesias military leader 
gen suharto was rounding up pki cadres and was determined to 
annihilate the party 
martens said he dealt with suharto loyalists who were opposed 
to thenpresident sukarno and his support for the left wing 
sukarno opposed the crackdown but he had lost power to such an 
extent that he effectively relinquished his post to suharto in 1966 
suharto has beens president since 1968 
martens said he made the decision to provide the names thinking 
it was standard practice to share information with host governments 
and that it wasnt a big deal 
he said he hadnt consulted with his superiors and only told 
them about it several years later 
the former deputy chief of the cia station in jakarta joseph 
lazarsky and martens boss edward masters said cia employees 
contributed to the pki lists according to a report published 
monday by states news service a small washingtonbased news 
service 
states news service reported that us officials used martens 
list to check off the names of pki members who were killed it said 
a 1968 cia report estimated the number of those killed at 250000 
cia spokesman mark mansfield denied that the agency was involved 
in the preparation or distribution of a list used to track down pki 
members 
state department spokesman richard boucher said pki leaders were 
well known to indonesian authorities 
its highly unlikely that we could have provided any 
information which was not known to the indonesian government of the 
time boucher said and of course we would not have provided 
names of people for the purposes of having them killed 
martens said the government had not put together any names 
because it was petrified by the assassination of six 
anticommunist generals the military blamed the killings on the 
pki and launched the purge that virtually destroyed the party 
</TEXT>
