<TEXT>
new evidence casts doubt on the convictions of 
seven people accused of running an irish republican army bomb 
factory in the 1970s the legal counsel for a judicial inquiry said 
monday 
tests that found traces of nitroglycerine on the hands of the 
seven defendants were insufficient to sustain their convictions 
said david clarke in an opening statement to a judicial inquiry 
the inquiry conducted by sir john may has no power to reverse 
the convictions it may be a year before the inquiry makes its 
recommendations to the government 
british courts in the past 12 months have reversed the 
convictions of four people accused of ira bombings and three others 
convicted of plotting to assassinate a british government official 
earlier this year home secretary david waddington ordered a 
review of the convictions of six men for ira bombings in birmingham 
that killed 21 people in 1974 that review has not been completed 
no explosives were found in the possession of the seven 
defendants currently under review but they were convicted of 
possessing explosives 
their convictions were based on tests and on statements made by 
two men convicted of killing seven people in pub bombings in 
guildford and woolwich in 1974 
those men and two others convicted of the pub bombings were 
freed last year after prosecutors admitted that police lied about 
statements made by the defendants 
following their release may a former appeal court judge was 
appointed to conduct an inquiry into the guildford and woolwich 
case and the related conviction in 1976 of four members of the 
maguire family two relatives and a friend 
the test used in the case known as thinlayer chromatography 
or tlc is a reliable test for nitroglycerine clarke said 
in a nutshell the results of the tlc tests viewed now with 
the benefit of hindsight did not of themselves prove that there 
had been in the house a bulk or quantity of explosive which 
had been handled by all the defendants clarke said 
but they do suggest that there had been at least a secondary 
source that is to say a person who had been in contact with a 
primary source that person need not have been one of the 
defendants 
clarke said one of the defendants may have handled a glass or 
towel previously touched by someone who had handled nitroglycerine 
convicted in the case were patrick maguire his wife anne and 
sons vincent and patrick guiseppe conlon husband of patrick 
maguires sister sean john smyth mrs maguires brother and 
family friend patrick joseph oneill 
conlon whose son gerard was convicted in the guildford case 
died in prison the others have completed their sentences 
police began investigating the maguires after statements by paul 
hill and later by gerard conlon identifying anne maguire as a bomb 
maker hill and conlon have said their statements were obtained 
under duress 
clarke said it was impossible to regard any of the maguire 
convictions as safe the standard used by the court of appeal 
in reversing the guildford convictions 
