<TEXT>
the food and drug administration on monday 
approved use of a live but weakened bacteria to treat a type of 
bladder cancer 
the product bacillus calmette guerin live or bcg live was 
approved to treat bladder cancer referred to as carcinoma in 
situ this type constitutes 20 to 30 percent of the 45000 cases 
of bladder cancer detected in the united states each year the fda 
said 
the treatment calls for the bacteria to be administered directly 
to the bladder through a catheter to attack the cancer cells on the 
lining of the organ the inflammation that results eliminates many 
of the cancer cells 
studies sponsored by the national cancer institute found that 74 
percent of patients with carcinoma in situ of the bladder responded 
to bcg treatment of those the median time for recurrence of the 
cancer was four years the fda said 
the most common side effects of the treatment are flulike 
symptoms such as fever chills and nausea and bladder discomfort 
however the fdaapproved labeling also warns physicians to 
watch for spread of the bcg organism throughout the body this the 
fda said has been associated with two deaths 
treatment with bcg is given once a week for six weeks and then 
monthly for six to 12 months 
the product is made by connaught laboratories ltd of 
willowdale ontario canada it will be marketed under the trade 
name theracys 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

