<TEXT>
the house began debate monday over the first 
strengthening of clean air laws in 13 years while closeddoor 
negotiations appeared unlikely to head off a floor fight over a 
tougher smogcontrol proposal 
the house was expected to vote on a series of about a halfdozen 
amendments to the bill later in the week with a final vote on the 
legislation expected by thursday 
the senate already has approved a clean air bill 
the legislation before the house won overwhelming approval from 
the energy and commerce committee in april its major provisions 
including major cuts in acid rain pollutants reduction in smog 
causing auto emissions and controls on toxic industrial releases 
are unlikely to be changed dramatically during floor action 
the legislations cost to the economy because of new 
pollutioncontrol requirements has been put at about 21 billion a 
year when all its provisions go into effect 
as floor debate began on the bill key congressmen and staff 
aides worked to reach compromise agreements on about a halfdozen 
amendments with an aim toward avoiding as many contentuous floor 
battles as possible 
but parties to the discussions said a floor fight has become 
almost unavoidable on a proposed amendment by rep henry waxman 
dcalif that calls for the annual production of 1 million 
nongasoline powered automobiles for sale in the nine us cities 
with the highest air pollution 
the cities are los angeles san diego houston chicago 
milwaukee baltimore new york philadelphia and hartford conn 
the measure would make the bills smogcontrolling auto emission 
requiring significantly tougher than the senate version which has 
no production requirement 
the auto industry has launched an allout campaign to block the 
proposal arguing that it would require manufacturers to rush such 
cars into production without clear evidence there would be a market 
for them 
waxman speaking on the house floor characterized his proposal 
as nothing more than what president bush had sought nearly a year 
ago when he included as part of his clean air proposal a 
requirement for alternativefuel vehicles 
but the white house backed away from imposing a production 
requirement after intense lobbying from the auto industry 
the senate defeated efforts to impose a similar requirement as 
did waxmans own energy and commerce subcommittee both 
environmentalists and auto industry lobbyists predicted a close 
vote on the amendment when it comes to the house floor 
in opening remarks in the floor debate rep john dingell 
dmich the energy and commerce committee chairman who has long 
been protective of the auto industrys interests suggested that 
most controversies on the clean air legislation have been largely 
eliminated 
dingell characterized the remaining issues of disagreement as 
being not environmental in character but rather differences of 
views among congressmen 
meanwhile compromise agreements were reported monday to have 
been worked out on several amendments assuring their swift 
approval when brought to the floor these included 
a requirement to sell in the nine cities with the worst smog 
problem a cleaner gasoline blend that has a specific oxygen 
content allowing it to burn cleaner the oil industry vigorously 
opposed the measure calling it tilted toward the use of ethenol 
which comes from grain 
require the environmental protection agency within two years to 
develop regulations on regional haze near major federal parks and 
wilderness areas environmentalists have claimed the epa has been 
slow in curbing air pollution in such areas 
streamline some provisions of the permitting and enforcement 
section of the bill to ease the paperwork burden to some businesses 
other amendments likely to be taken up on the house floor 
include a provision broading the required phaseout of a variety of 
atmospheric ozonedamaging chemicals in addition to 
chloroflurocarbons or cfcs and an amendment that would impose 
federal air pollution requirements on offshore oildrilling 
platforms 
