<TEXT>
the operator of a kentucky mine where 10 
workers died in an explosion last year was cited monday for 121 
alleged violations of federal safety laws 
the labor departments mine safety and health administration 
said 42 violations against pyro mining co involved reckless 
disregard of safety the highest degree of negligence in the 
agencys penalty system 
the number and nature of the violations show a lack of concern 
about safety on the part of the operator as well as poor safety 
management said william tattersall assistant secretary of labor 
for mine safety and health 
james greenlee executive vice president of costain coal inc 
which owns pyro said the company was reviewing the alleged 
violations to determine whether it will request a conference with 
federal investigators to give them more information about safety 
procedures 
companies are allowed to provide additional information before 
the agency proposes fines for alleged safety violations 
eventually pyro mining could face civil penalties of up to 10000 
for each violation 
an agency report earlier this month said 10 specific violations 
contributed to the sept 13 explosion in wheatcroft ky most of 
the violations identified monday had nothing to do with the cause 
of the blast but we still consider them serious tattersall 
said 
the agency report released may 8 said an investigation showed 
that pyro mining managers knew explosive methane gas was 
accumulating in the mine four days before the explosion but they 
did not maintain adequate records that would have alerted the 
others 
that report alleged that managers failed to make required checks 
for the deadly gas in the hours before the explosion failed to 
keep enough clean air in the mine to clear out methane and made a 
series of changes in air pathways that caused a methane buildup the 
day of the disaster 
federal investigators were unable to determine exactly what 
triggered the explosion 
mondays announcement said investigators looking for possible 
ignition sources found 65 electrical violations in cables and 
circuits one electrical cable had 36 splices all of which had 
been improperly made tattersall said 
investigators also found 41 violations concerning ventilation 
and preshift safety examinations another 15 citations involved 
miscellaneous safety violatings including blasting caps 
haphazardly left in the work area 
