<TEXT>
north yemens prowestern parliament on 
monday approved a plan by president ali abdullah saleh to merge 
tuesday with socialist south yemen official radio reports in north 
yemen said 
the reports said the 159member shura council or parliament 
had agreed with a sweeping majority to merge the two yemens 
which are among the worlds least developed states sana the 
north yemeni capital is to serve as capital of the newly named 
yemen republic 
south yemens parliament the supreme peoples council also 
held a special session to approve the unification of the two red 
sea nations 
a united yemen would be the second such union between two arab 
states in this century in the 1950s egypt and syria joined as the 
united arab republic but the merger collapsed after three years 
because of internal squabbling 
the new state would bind together 11 million people nine 
million from the north and two million from the south 
south yemen was the arab worlds only avowedly marxist state 
after it gained independence from britain in 1971 
but yemen began to reform as democratic changes swept through 
the soviet union and eastern europe 
the two yemens are poor and undeveloped labor unrest in south 
yemen has been aggravated in recent months as western goods were 
transported from north yemen to the south 
strikes mushroomed in most government offices and factories in 
south yemen 
the merger bid has been outwardly promoted by oilrich nations 
on the arabian peninsula such as saudi arabia which is eager to 
snuff out soviet influence 
scores of cuban and east german military experts are said to 
have left aden the capital of south yemen in recent months a 
friendship pact entitles the soviets to maintain as many as 18000 
troops in the port city but the extent of their deployment is 
unknown 
the merger was originally planned for nov 30 but it was moved 
up to may 26 in recent days there had been pressure to speed up 
the schedule even more so the two yemens can attend an emergency 
arab summit on may 28 in baghdad iraq as one state 
shortly after the start of the session of south yemens 
