<TEXT>
panels of medical experts on monday 
recommended stronger efforts to ensure that the acne drug accutane 
is not taken during pregnancy because it can cause birth defects 
but the two food and drug administration advisory committees 
rejected the advice of some within the agency who want accutane 
withheld from all women to eliminate any risk of birth defects from 
the drug 
the manufacturer hoffmanlaroche said it was pleased with the 
recommendations which it said were close to additional warnings it 
announced earlier in the day 
accutane which has been on the market since 1982 is the best 
treatment for severe recalcitrant cystic acne a disfiguring and 
debilitating form of acne but a woman who takes the drug during 
pregnancy has a 1in4 chance of having a baby with serious birth 
defects 
the committee actions came as other physicians were reporting 
that accutane can significantly block the growth of new tumors in 
people being treated for smokingrelated cancer of the mouth and 
throat 
in september 1988 roche dermatologics a division of 
hoffmanlaroche began a pregnancy prevention program aimed at 
emphasizing and educating physicians about the importance of 
avoiding pregancy during treatment 
roche officials say 86 cases of birth defects have been reported 
to the company as being associated with accutane since the drug was 
first marketed 
but david graham an fda medical epidemiologist said that 
number represents only about 10 percent of the number that actually 
occur he estimated that since 1982 nearly 1000 babies have been 
born with birth defects because their mothers were using accutane 
graham also estimated that about 90 percent of the women using 
accutane do not have the severe form of acne for which the drug is 
indicated 
accutane was prescribed last year for about 65000 women of 
childbearing age but the estimated annual incidence of severe 
recalcitrant cystic acne in this group of women is less than 4000 
graham said 
the overprescribing exposes tens of thousands of women to the 
possibility of a malformed child if they become pregnant while 
being treated he said it also increases the likelihood of 
abortion he said 
citing a michigan medicaid study he said women using accutane 
had twice as many abortions as women not using the drug 
he said roches pregnancy prevention program has failed to 
achieve its objective 
the only way to eliminate exposure is to eliminate use of this 
drug by women he said 
robert armstrong director of medical affairs for roche 
dermatologics said grahams estimates were based on shaky 
assumptions 
he also said that no one is sure how many women have the severe 
acne but he said he was sure the number of congenital 
malformations that result from accutane are not as large as graham 
believes 
if there were that many out there they would be noticed and 
reported armstrong said 
the fdas advisory committees on dermatologic drugs and 
fertility and maternal health drugs recommended by general 
consensus that the company emphasize in its program the importance 
of a pregnancy test before a patient starts using accutane 
the panels also recommended a program for patients to return any 
unused accutane at the end of treatment and that forms to record 
patient consent now available in english and spanish be available 
in more languages additionally the panels said physicians should 
be encouraged to refer accutane patients for contraception 
counseling 
roche announced earlier in the day it was supplementing its 
pregnancy prevention program to stress the importance of the first 
pregnancy test which roche will offer to pay for and which must 
show no pregnancy before therapy can begin 
other new measures include steppedup advertising aimed at 
physicians possible development of a special prescription pad to 
reinforce the warnings provision of an illustration of a deformed 
infant in the package literature and development of a method to 
return unused accutane 
</TEXT>
