<TEXT>
more than 300000 medical laboratories 
including those in physicians offices would have to meet federal 
standards under regulations proposed monday 
the regulations written by the department of health and human 
services are aimed at assuring the quality and accuracy of medical 
tests said hhs secretary louis sullivan 
under our plan every laboratory regardless of its location 
must be federally certified as meeting quality standards he 
said labs must prove they can perform their tests correctly 
under the proposal laboratory tests would be divided into three 
categories 
tests that are complex and pose a high risk if done incorrectly 
such as pap smears to test for cervical cancer and simpler tests 
with some risk like cholesterol screening would be subject to 
federal standards 
twentyeight tests that hhs describes as simple with lowrisk 
such as dipstick urinalysis would be waived from regulation 
labs that fail to comply with federal requirements for quality 
control personnel qualifications and proficiency testing could 
have their certification revoked suspended or limited or suffer 
other civil penalties 
the regulation would implement a law passed by congress in 1988 
after reports about inaccuracies in pap smear tests 
</TEXT>
