the study put together with information from wolf experts from 
throughout the world and researchers from three universities 
predicts little impact on wildlife or livestock near yellowstone if 
wolves are returned 
however it speculates that some wolves would leave 
yellowstones boundaries and have to be controlled by one means or 
another to protect livestock interests 
while some critics of the recovery plan fear wolves would 
decimate yellowstones big game herds the study said the available 
prey base was at least five times greater than that which 100 
wolves the ideal recovery population would be expected to 
reduce or even limit 
the study said at least 30 wolves would have to be released 
initially to assure the programs success it also suggested that 
wolves returned to yellowstone be considered a nonessential 
experimental population so biologists would have freer rein in 
controlling them than if they were covered by the full endangered 
species act 
it also calls for more studies on the predator and the park 
service has budgeted 175000 for that work this fiscal year 
bryce dustman press secretary for sen conrad burns a montana 
republican who is opposed to the wolf program said he wasnt 
surprised by the reports claim that wolves would have little 
effect on wildlife or livestock 
he said it jumped out at him that the two leading proponents 
of wolf restoration in yellowstone the park service and fish and 
wildlife service wrote a study saying the wolf wouldnt have a 
detrimental affect on livestock or big game 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

