for the fee arrangement 
some cases are exceedingly complex some are extremely long 
said lehtinen it would be reasonable for counsel to be appointed 
by the court and those fees paid by the government 
the judge set at hearing for thursday to discuss details of the 
fees 
defense attorney frank rubino said he was satisfied with the 
proposal 
we do concur with them we think this particular section of 
the law may solve the problem in extreme cases of this nature 
he said 
rubino said noriega who was in court but did not testify 
agreed to sign affidavits declaring he was indigent and that if his 
assets were freed he would repay the federal government 
rubino has said noriega received 11 million from the united 
states for information about drug smuggling along with 6 million 
or 7 million from as yet unidentified foreign countries 
prosecutors acknowledge that the united states paid noriega but 
dispute the details 
the government believes that the amount is substantially less 
than that offered by the defense counsel diane cossin 
spokeswoman for the us attorneys office said monday i cannot 
be more specific because that information is not public 
one account alone in the united kingdom has about 10 million 
in it said defense attorney steven kollin under classified 
information rules governing the trial the attorneys could not say 
whose name was on the account but exchanges in court indicate it 
may be the name of noriegas wife 
there is money in that account and thats what were fighting 
for kollin said 
hoeveler had urged prosecutors to expedite action on the asset 
issue saying he views the question of attorneys fees as extremely 
important 
the judge has expressed skepticism of government claims that the 
money is all drugrelated saying as a military officer and leader 
of a country noriega must have had legitimate income 
noriega was indicted in february 1988 on charges of accepting 
46 million in bribes from the medellin cartel in exchange for 
turning panama into a safe haven and transit point to support 
cocaine smuggling into the united states 
he turned himself in to us authorities on jan 4 two weeks 
after the invasion of panama and was flown to florida where he is 
being held at the federal metropolitan correctional center outside 
of miami 
</TEXT>
