<DOCNO> AP900521-0179 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
vermont supreme court justice louis peck 
can remain on the bench even though he is past the states 
mandatory retirement age for judges a federal appeals court ruled 
monday 
the ruling by the 2nd us circuit court of appeals comes almost 
a year after peck was scheduled to be retired by the state because 
he had turned 70 
the state constitution calls on all judges to retire at age 70 
but peck had fought the provision saying it conflicted with a 
federal age discrimination law 
i feel like a condemned man who has had a reprieve said 
peck monday night after learning of the decision personally it 
is very satisfying 
peck now 71 said he will now give some thought to stepping 
down i may retire anyway he said 
the ruling by the new yorkbased federal appeals court settles 
the peck case but it does not settle the issue two other federal 
appeals courts the 8th circuit and 1st circuit have ruled the 
other way on the question which means judges in those 
jurisdictions must adhere to their states mandatory retirement 
provisions 
obviously congress has not made its intention clear if the 
court disagree said william gray the lawyer who represented the 
state of vermont in the suit against peck 
gray said it would be several weeks before the state decided 
whether it would appeal to the us supreme court 
taking away from states the power to decide when they retire 
their judges is a major shift of power from the states said gray 
thomas lehner the state court administrator said he had not 
seen the decision and would not comment until he had 
at issue was whether a federal law the federal age 
discrimination and employment act applied to appointed state 
judges the law prohibits age discrimination against most employees 
the state of vermont argued first that judges fit one of the 
exceptions appointees on the policymaking level and second 
that congress should not tell states how to set up their courts 
on the first argument the appeals court said appointed state 
judges do not fall under the exception congress meant to deny 
adea protection only to such appointees as would normally work 
closely with and be accountable to the official who appointed 
them the judges said 
on the second argument the judges said vermont had failed to 
show the federal law improperly trampled on the rights of the 
states there is no suggestion that congress surreptitiously 
enacted any legislation without notice to the state of vermont 
the court said 
the decision by the new yorkbased 2nd circuit counters rulings 
by the bostonbased 1st us circuit court of appeals and the st 
louisbased 8th us circuit court of appeals those federal 
appeals courts upheld state mandatory retirement provisions 
peck was appointed to the vermont supreme court in 1981 his 
current term expires in 1993 he turned 70 on dec 24 1988 
prompting lehner to place him on retirement status effective june 
30 1989 and prompting peck to file an age discrimination 
complaint with the eeoc which filed suit on his behalf last july 
us district judge lee gagliardi sided with peck prompting the 
appeal by the state to the 2nd circuit 
the vermont supreme court has five members it is the only 
appeals court in the state 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

