<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
may 1421 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
responding to a 51 percent decline in 
earnings during the first quarter mcclatchy newspapers inc says 
it is braced for more potential bad news this year and is cutting 
costs 
officials at the companys annual meeting may 16 blamed the 
decline on falling ad sales for newspapers across the country 
retail ad linage softened dramatically in march at most of our 
papers as it did throughout most of the country and resulted in a 
very disappointing first quarter said erwin potts president and 
chief executive officer of the company which publishes the 
sacramento bee and 18 other newspapers in four states 
treasurer james p smith said net firstquarter income fell from 
48 million in 1989 to 24 million in 1990 
smith also attributed the lower profits in part to interest 
expense from mcclatchys recent purchase of several south carolina 
papers and on startup costs for a newsprint mill in washington 
state 
we may yet take some tough hits before 1990 is over said 
potts if ad linage remains low we expect that things will 
rebound if not later this year then certainly next year 
on the positive side potts said circulation has continued to 
grow in the past five years at all mcclatchys major papers but 
one which is in an area of washington state hurt financially by 
the shutdown of a nuclear power plant 
the sacramento bee led the circulation growth last year with 
daily circulation up 53 percent and sunday up 52 percent 
for mcclatchy newspapers revenues totaled 381 million in 1989 
up 7 percent from the previous year smith said advertising 
revenues totaled 303 million and circulation revenues 63 million 
he said 
net income totaled 34 million up from 29 million in 1988 and 
representing a 31 percent increase over the past four years smith 
said 
the company on wednesday declared a regular quarterly cash 
dividend of 4 cents per share payable july 3 1990 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
j stewart bryan iii whose family started 
in the newspaper business in richmond 140 years ago was chosen may 
18 to succeed his father as board chairman of media general inc 
the board of directors also elected him president and chief 
executive officer replacing james s evans who was elected vice 
chairman bryan is also a member of the board of directors of the 
associated press 
his father d tennant bryan 83 will become chairman of the 
media general boards executive committee 
media general is the parent company of richmond newspapers inc 
which publishes the richmond timesdispatch and the richmond news 
leader 
media general also owns the winstonsalem journal in north 
carolina and the tampa tribune in florida three television 
stations two cable television companies and a 40 percent stake in 
the new jerseybased garden state newspapers 
under evans direction the company has trimmed its holdings 
under a restructuring plan to focus on its core east coast media 
interests one of the biggest changes was the sale last year of two 
groups of community weekly newspapers in los angeles and orange 
counties in california 
stewart bryan said the industry has been in the doldrums but 
that earnings would be robust this year he would not give an 
estimate 
bryan also said the company expects nearterm growth will be 
internal and that no major acquisitions are envisioned 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the sole investor in kansas citys 
new afternoon newspaper says he hopes to buck a national trend and 
attract enough readers for a profit analysts say thats going to 
be tough 
the first edition of the kansas city evening news rolled off the 
press may 14 
steve rose president of a familyowned chain of 18 suburban 
weekly papers and owner of the new 50cent tabloid said the paper 
sold about 22800 copies its first day 
media analysts contend the newspaper will face tough times 
because of a general decline in advertising revenues 
rose said he can make a profit through low costs small 
circulation and street sales the newspaper will not be delivered 
to homes 
he said hes not trying to compete directly with the kansas city 
star a morning paper with daily circulation of 297000 
rose said he got the idea for a newspaper in march when the 
kansas city star co stopped publishing an afternoon edition and 
merged it with the morning newspaper after years of declining 
afternoon circulation 
i dont want and i dont need 50000 to 100000 readers 
rose said if we start down that path suddenly all the economies 
change thats exactly where ralph ingersoll ended up 
ingersoll started the tabloid st louis sun to compete with the 
st louis postdispatch for morning readers but the sun shut down 
last month after only seven months ingersoll cited homedelivery 
costs and inadequate street sales 
roses newspaper unlike the much larger st louis sun has an 
editorial staff of four it will consist mostly of news from wire 
services 
the mondaythroughfriday paper shares a press building and 
other equipment with roses weeklies startup costs have been under 
1 million he said 
ken berents an analyst for alex brown amp sons inc in new york 
said starting a new newspaper in a town with a monopoly newspaper 
like kansas city is like running uphill with ankle weights on 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the state supreme court ruled may 17 that a 
circuit judge acted illegally when he restricted reporters covering 
a trial stemming from an alleged rape at the south dakota 
governors mansion 
the high court said in a unanimous decision that circuit judge 
marshall young of rapid city must rescind his order young had 
threatened reporters with arrest if they published the names of 
people involved in the march trial of two juveniles 
gov george mickelson has acknowledged that his son david was 
one of the two 
youngs order was illegal because he failed to hold a hearing 
before issuing it made it too broad and required law enforcement 
officers to enforce possible violations of the order the supreme 
court said 
however the justices declined to rule on the constitutionality 
of the state law on which the circuit judges order was based 
the sioux falls argus leader and the associated press had argued 
that the law which prohibits the publication of names of people 
involved in juvenile court proceedings was an unconstitutional 
prior restraint on the news medias right to publish lawfully 
obtained information 
young presided over a closeddoor trial of two 17yearold boys 
charged with sex offenses in connection with a nov 28 incident at 
the governors mansion after the twoday trial the judge 
acquitted one boy of nonforcible rape and acquitted the other of 
aiding and abetting rape 
the two boys and a third 17yearold admitted to charges of 
underage drinking and were given probation and ordered to do 
community work young also ordered that the two boys who had been 
charged with sex offenses must each pay onehalf the medical 
expenses of the alleged rape victim a 16yearold girl 
