<TEXT>
the first amendment doesnt exempt 
reporters from the obligation of testifying about crimes they 
witness floridas supreme court said in rejecting an appeal by the 
miami herald 
while we are mindful of the importance of a vigorous and 
aggressive press we fail to see how compelling a reporter to 
testify concerning his eyewitness observations of a relevant event 
in a criminal proceeding in any way chills or impinges on the 
newsgathering process justice parker lee mcdonald wrote for the 
majority 
the herald floridas largest newspaper hasnt decided if it 
will appeal the may 17 decision said attorney samuel terilli jr 
he said the ruling would have a limited impact because it was 
written to cover only a narrow specific set of circumstances 
it applies only to reporters who have eyewitnessed crimes 
searches and similar events in criminal cases and that just 
doesnt happen too often terilli said 
reporter joel achenbach was subpoenaed by an attorney for a new 
york man arrested on drug smuggling charges at the miami 
international airport achenbach was accompanying three metrodade 
police officers at the time as part of his research for an article 
details of the search and arrest in achenbachs story differed 
from police reports 
a state trial court and floridas 3rd district court of appeal 
rejected the heralds argument that the first amendment to the us 
constitution extended to achenbach a qualified privilege to refuse 
to divulge information obtained firsthand as a witness to an event 
in a criminal case 
</TEXT>
