<TEXT>
public televisions the macneillehrer 
newshour features more whites and males and is more 
governmentoriented and conservative than abcs nightline says 
a group that studied both shows 
the assertion was made by a liberal media watchdog group 
fairness amp accuracy in reporting in a study released may 20 fair 
president jeff cohen said the pbs show has a narrow 
proestablishment guest list that mocks the original mandate of 
public television to provide diversity 
newshour executive producer les crystal said the news 
program agrees that diversity is important and we clearly feel we 
can and should do better in that regard 
but he disputed what he called fairs contention that the show 
doesnt criticize the government much and asks onesided questions 
the fair study of newshour broadcasts from feb 6 to aug 4 
1989 was conducted by boston college sociologists william hoynes 
and david croteau who made a study critical of nightline last 
year 
the nightline report examining 40 months of the abc 
program from 1985 to 1988 found that 89 percent of its guests were 
men 92 percent were white and that conservative leaders were the 
shows most frequent guests 
fairs new study entitled all the usual suspects 
macneillehrer and nightline also compared abcs program with 
newshour during the same sixmonth period the latter was 
studied 
the two professors making the study found that abcs show has 
slightly broadened its guest list since the original study but 
that our hopes for significant change were not met 
their newshour study found that of us citizens appearing 
as guests 90 percent of them were white and 87 percent were male 
the figures rose on programs about international politics it said 
with 94 percent of us citizens appearing to discuss world 
politics being both white and male 
the study offered no racial or gender percentages for guests who 
were not us citizens 
it characterized as more representative the guests invited 
when the shows topic was domestic politics it said that 26 
percent of them were women but gave no figures on the race of 
female guests 
fairs study said the shows guest list was dominated by two 
conservative washington think tanks with a total of 14 guests 
provided by the center for strategic and international studies and 
the american enterprise institute 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
news organizations asked the illinois 
supreme court on may 18 to allow cameras and microphones in the 
states trial courts 
the best way for the public to have confidence in its judicial 
system is to see whats going on said richard thies an attorney 
for illinois news broadcasters association one of the petitioners 
before 1984 cameras and microphones werent allowed in any 
state courts but that year the supreme court opened the doors of 
appellate courts 
the justices decided to keep cameras and microphones out of the 
trial courts because of fears that miscarriages of justice will 
result from the subtle insidious effect that televising trials 
will have upon the behavior of the participants in court 
proceedings former justice robert underwood wrote at the time 
when that decision was made 30 states allowed cameras and 
microphones in trial courts now 37 states allow cameras and 
microphones in trial courts and thies said the experience of those 
states has shown camera coverage doesnt affect the outcome of 
trials 
electronic coverage of trials would help guarantee due process 
by encouraging public scrutiny of trials thus acting as a direct 
check on abuse of the judicial process he wrote in the brief 
submitted to the high court 
thies said news organizations are hoping the supreme court will 
adopt a rule similar to new yorks test program 
the new york rule allows microphones and cameras in trial courts 
but prohibits taping of rape victims jurors and undercover 
officers it also prohibits audio coverage of conferences among 
attorneys clients and the judge 
thies said he didnt expect the court to rule on his request 
before next year 
other petitioners are wls television inc wmaqtv the illinois 
broadcasters association the illinois press photographers 
association and the illinois freedom of information council 
</TEXT>
