<TEXT>
so there really is a credit crunch after all 
despite the federal reserves earlier comment that it could find 
none in its regular data 
this crunch however seems not to be directly managed by the 
fed whose job it is to regulate the flow of funds to the banks 
and therefore to the economy it is managed instead by the banks 
themselves 
it is you might say a privatesector clampdown one in which 
the banks have funds available to them but arent making funds 
available to businesses especially small ones and those involved 
with commercial real estate 
the information from a survey by the fed itself tends to 
resolve what had seemed to be a contradiction small businesses 
complaining they couldnt get sufficient credit but the fed 
indicating it wasnt tightening the flow 
regardless of the source business again feels it is victimized 
it makes no difference who is the source of their distress the 
feds or the bankers since the impact is the same 
operators of small businesses especially say it is an old story 
recalling that just a decade ago the prime lending rate rose to 
215 percent for the very best corporate customers for small 
businesses it was more like 25 percent 
that 1981 crunch was federal reservegenerated and many 
businesses ranging from proprietorships to some with sales close 
to 50 million a year succumbed or were bought up it was one of 
the worst recessions ever 
in fact by some measures the early 1980s recession was the 
deepest since the great depression of the 1930s a debacle some 
historians say was worsened when the fed tightened up early in that 
decade and loosened too late 
some business people still argue in fact that the doubledigit 
interest rates that developed in the late 1970s were due as much to 
fed miscalculation as to the robustness of business and consumer 
spending 
first the critics say the fed allowed too much credit into the 
economy and then it clamped down with unnecessary harshness but 
inflation was roaring and that meant higher interest rates were 
required they said 
you still cant sell that argument to some fed critics they 
contend that inflation then wasnt a result of consumer and 
business demand straining the nations capacity to produce they 
say it was eurodollars 
eurodollars are us dollars made abroad when americans import 
more than they export european banks which hold the dollars make 
dollardenominated loans based on the dollars they have on deposit 
dollars flood the world 
the fed the critics say restrained the us economy by 
limiting the ability of business to borrow but the creation of 
dollars by foreign banks was left unregulated it was those 
dollars they say that created inflation 
now the crackdown seems to be by the banks themselves according 
to the fed survey the fed itself has not tightened up on the money 
supply in fact it says it decided not to raise interest rates at 
a policy meeting in march 
why should the banks be cautious that answer too is an old one 
because they are worried having made bad loans that must be worked 
off the books foreign loans now essentially uncollectable and 
bad real estate loans 
and smaller businesses those not on the fortune lists and most 
of them not likely ever to be there are feeling the pinch nothing 
new in that either any smallbusiness person can show you the 
welts left by earlier crackdowns 
it matters not whether it is the federal reserve or a 
privatesector lender who does the whipping the welts are the same 
color 
</TEXT>
