<TEXT>
regulars at the peking gourmet 
inn know that when secret service agents suddenly swarm through the 
front door president bush is returning for another feast at his 
favorite chinese restaurant 
bush in fact might be called a regular himself general 
manager robert tsui says bush has visited the peking gourmet inn 
about 15 times since his first visit on sept 2 1985 when he was 
vice president and a guest of his son marvin 
the next day bush sat down at a typewriter and tapped out a 
glowing testimonial letter to owner eddie tsui roberts father 
that other restaurateurs would kill for 
i just wanted you to know that the food was excellent 
bush wrote your family swung into action and provided terrific 
hospitality and delicious food the duck especially was 
fantastic 
the letter is framed and hangs on a wall surrounded by 
autographed photos of bush sometimes wearing a blue sports shirt 
enjoying the restaurants northern chinese cuisine with his wife 
barbara and their guests who have included attorney general dick 
thornburgh and british ambassador sir antony acland 
bush learned about chinese food while serving as chief us 
liaison officer in beijing in 197475 before diplomatic relations 
between the two countries were restored robert tsui says the 
presidents tastes are wellinformed 
on one visit bush held a detailed 20minute discussion with 
roberts younger brother executive chef george tsui about the 
ingredients of various dishes on the menu i think he knows 
chinese food very well robert tsui said 
the tsui family says bushs visits every few months are relaxed 
casual affairs with friends and family that seem to be arranged on 
the spur of the moment 
instead of spending months arranging it mr bush calls 
personally in the afternoon and says hes coming that evening 
said robert tsui boom its done he takes everyone by surprise 
even some of his guests 
its only a 15minute drive from the white house south across 
the potomac river to the peking gourmet inn situated in one of the 
older neighborhood shopping centers in suburban fairfax county va 
bush usually leaves the choice of dishes to george tsui who is 
familiar with the presidents likes and dislikes we have known 
for a long time that no broccoli is to be served robert tsui 
said 
george keeps the secret service out of his large kitchen it 
makes the chefs nervous he says and he helps longtime waiter 
tak chung pang carry each course from the kitchen to the 
presidential partys large round table behind a plush red partition 
in the dining room 
tsui says bushs favorite is szechuan beef proper a sweet and 
spicy shredded beef served with roasted sesame seeds 
he says the president also is fond of the peking duck a house 
specialty and the four seasons string beans szechuan style a 
blend of string beans and tiny morsels of pork seasoned with ginger 
and garlic and cooked in chicken stock 
the president usually pays the bill by writing a personal check 
but occasionally autographs the bill and promises to mail payment 
you know where to send the bill bush once told his hosts 
the tsui children built the restaurant in 1978 as a retirement 
gift for their father eddie now 77 a native of shandong province 
in china who emigrated to the united states 14 years ago after 
running a couple of restaurants in hong kong 
much of the fresh foods used in the peking gourmet inns kitchen 
are grown on the tsui familys 133acre farm near rural 
purcellville va 40 miles to the west their homegrown produce 
includes giant spring onions chinese chives or leeks peppers 
celery eggplant garlic and garlic sprouts a delicacy cultivated 
in underground caves 
