<TEXT>
 
sea of love mca home entertainment vhsbeta no suggested 
retail price rated r 
 
sea of love might better be called ocean of despair or 
tide of terror with its dual themes of lonely hearts and 
vicious murders 
director harold becker has crafted a taut suspense based on a 
series of murders that have one thing in common all the victims 
had placed ads in a singles column of a new york magazine 
in grisly fashion the killer has the men lay naked face down on 
a bed and pretend to make love before shooting them in the back of 
the head 
two homicide detectives al pacino and john goodman set out to 
find the killer by placing an ad of their own believing the 
murderer a woman will respond and fal into their trap 
enter ellen barkin mysterious leggy and too alluring for 
pacinos own good as one of the ads respondents she becomes a 
suspect as easily as she becomes pacinos lover 
barkin perfectly plays the role its impossible to tell if 
shes a cunning killer or guarded sad heart hurt once too often in 
the dating danger zone and that quirky smile of hers one side 
sloping downward adds a hint of melancholy to even the lightest 
moments 
pacino who makes his return to film after a fouryear 
selfimposed absence is perfect as a paunchy divorced alcoholic 
his puffy glassy eyes seem to have seen too many dead bodies and 
too many bars at closing time 
the movie gets its gritty realism from the dialogue written by 
richard price who befriended new york cops to get little nuggets 
such as calling a victim a facedown taxpayer and calling the 
suspect a doer and a shooter 
if there is a flaw in this film its the pat ending that seems 
to put on a forced happy face perhaps hollywood executives demand 
audiences be given a warm fuzzy finish but viewers will find this 
one ingratiating and disappointing 
</TEXT>
