king blank to beggars banquet the ian lowery group 
 
restless singer ian lowerys career has taken him from the wall 
to ski patrol folk devils and a solo career as king blank thats 
four bands no hits 
now king blank has been renamed the ian lowery group for its 
second album king blank to the uninitiated will need to hear 
it just once to understand how fame has eluded lowery 
commercial hes not lowerys music can be described as 
neopunk dueling guitars recall television jarring chord 
progressions are reminiscent of richard hell and nihilistic singing 
suggests johnny rotten i need nobody or anything can you 
imagine lowery snarls in need 
the mixture results in a sound thats original and hard to 
dismiss theres a kind of recklessness to rockers such as never 
trust me and youre gonna pay that is bracing the energy 
flags only on the albums slowest songs wild times and the 
party 
best of all are lowerys lyrics he comes across like lou reed 
after an especially bad day at the office dark descriptions of 
life on the fringe shed new light on such subjects as betrayal 
revenge sex drugs and murder 
the standout cut is jack dust a banjodriven folk song with 
a violent storyline a sense of humor and several neat plot twists 
there ought to be a market for work this good 
by steven wine associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
peter and the wolf op 67 by sergei prokofiev the carnival of 
the animals emi philharmonia orchestra efrem kurtz conductor 
jonathan winters narrator 
 
welcome to the jonathan winters show the comedians name looms 
larger than the titles of the works on the booklet and his 
breathless bio comes first he also dominates this disc in just 
about every other way usually not to its advantage 
first his voice and the orchestra sound like they are in 
differemt rooms with the orchestra in the back of the house and 
winters close up in fact they sound separately recorded the 
orchestra meanwhile has a dull lifeless quality and the 
playing particularly in peter and the wolf is indifferent 
winters when reading the text lets a bored note creep into his 
voice he also frequently adds his own comments and imitations of 
the characters which generally dont equal what the music can do 
he follows with little asides identifying what hes imitating 
younger children might be disturbed to hear winters comment that 
the cat sounds like shed been run over by a car 
saintsaens musical bestiary comes off better winters sticks 
to the text and shows his brilliance as a mimic by using different 
accents for the charming and witty ogden nash verse that introduces 
each section ray clarks cello solo in the swan is longnecked 
and eloquent 
by daniel wakin associated press writer 
