grain and soybean futures prices were moderately 
lower in early trading this morning on the chicago board of trade 
pressured in part by forecasts for drier weather in the midwest and 
southeast 
heavy rain during the past two weeks has slowed corn planting 
and lowered yield prospects for winter wheat but the gradual 
clearing expected this week could allow farmers to get back into 
their fields said victor lespinasse an assistant vice president 
in the graintrading division of dean witter reynolds inc 
further selling stemmed from an agriculture department report 
released late friday that showed lighterthanexpected 
participation by farmers in the 1990 acreage setaside program 
which means farmers may plant more corn than the market had 
anticipated 
