<TEXT>
the number of working us oil and natural gas 
rigs rose for the third straight week increasing by 31 to total 
972 baker hughes inc reported monday 
in the past two weeks the rig count had posted increases of 
three and then 11 previously the count had declined for several 
weeks 
this weeks count also is well ahead of the 737 total posted a 
year ago baker hughes said 
the houstonbased companys rig count is the widely watched 
industry index of drilling activity it reflects the number of 
rotary rigs actively exploring for oil and gas as of last friday 
not the number of producing wells 
hughes tool co an oil toolmaker company that merged with baker 
international corp of orange calif has kept track of the rig 
count since 1940 
in december 1981 at the height of the oil boom the rig count 
reached a peak of 4500 but oil prices plunged to less than 10 
per 42gallon barrel in the summer of 1986 prompting a collapse in 
the rig count that bottomed out at 663 the lowest since hughes 
began compiling figures 
among major oilproducing states california posted the largest 
increase with 16 followed by oklahoma and louisiana which each 
gained nine rigs wyomings count increased by six kansas was up 
by four and pennsylvania and ohio gained one each 
texas lost three rigs colorado was down by two and michigan 
lost one 
