<TEXT>
motorola inc said monday it it will begin 
universal drug testing of its 60000 us employees this year 
apparently becoming the second major corporation to test all 
workers for substance abuse 
the giant electronics company based in suburban schaumburg has 
been testing job applicants since 1987 said spokeswoman margot 
brown motorola also has had a policy of testing of workers 
involved in accidents or exhibiting dangerous behavior 
under the expanded policy all employees will be tested within 
the next three years ms brown said 
motorola has experienced problems with drug use as have most 
other major corporations she said 
texas instruments inc another electronics manufacturer began 
universal drug testing in november 1989 said spokeswoman sandy 
christopher 
dallasbased texas instruments employs about 52000 people in 
the united states upper management was tested in the fourth 
quarter of 1989 and testing of all employees began jan 2 
theres been a very small percentage of employees whove 
complained about invasion of their privacy but surprisingly 
enough the employees are very supportive of the policy ms 
christopher said 
it gets into safety who wants to be working next to someone 
thats on drugs and to produce quality products its very 
important to have a drugfree workplace she said 
after seeking employee opinions ms brown of motorola said 
what we came up with was that a lot of our employees were 
concerned about a drug problem and felt that if we were going to do 
testing of our employees the only fair way to do it was to test 
all of them 
we feel our approach is balanced motorolans who dont abuse 
drugs will have a safe workplace and those who do abuse drugs will 
be offered help she added 
employees will be tested by urinalysis if that test is 
positive a second a more complex test will be used to check the 
results employees testing positive once will be offered 
confidential counseling and those testing positive twice will be 
dismissed 
neither companys workers are represented by unions 
the institute for a drugfree workplace in washington praised 
motorolas action 
i think its an excellent program and its one we have found 
that employees are increasingly supportive of said mark a de 
bernardo the institutes executive director 
a gallup poll in december showed 60 percent of american workers 
favor drug testing by their employers the percentage fell to 51 
percent when the 1007 workers were asked whether companies should 
be able to test any employee randomly 
the poll also showed 29 percent of the workers surveyed thought 
drug testing invaded privacy and should be done only under limited 
circumstances 
the poll with a 31 percent margin of error was commissioned 
by the institute a coalition of 14 large corporations concerned 
about employer rights in battling drug abuse both motorola and 
texas instruments are institute members 
the american civil liberties union opposes such testing 
because the test will eventually test all employees makes it 
no less an invasion of privacy than a totally random system said 
harvey grossman legal director of the illinois aclu chapter 
and the willingness of a majority of people to abandon their 
privacy rights doesnt in any way invalidate the feelings and the 
integrity of those who believe theyre entitled to their most basic 
and fundamental privacy interests despite someone paying them for 
an honest days work grossman said 
were not opposed to companies taking proper measures to 
ensure that employees performance is not impaired on the job 
particularly in safetyrelated issues said gene guerrero 
legislative representative for the aclus washington office 
but if you as an employer are concerned about safety and 
productivity use an impairment test dont run around telling 
people what they can do on their time off guerrero said 
</TEXT>
