all contracts for may deliveries of grains and soybeans expired 
at noon monday the may soybean contract went off the board at 
604 a bushel may wheat expired at 383 may corn at 280 and 
may oats at 144 
july soybeans have dropped by 50 cents a bushel since may 10 
when the agriculture department issued a report projecting a 
bountiful 1990 harvest of 19 billion bushels and an increase in 
the us soybean stockpile 
analysts said rising south american soybean exports have 
bolstered perceptions that brazil and argentina can handle current 
global demand and at prices that are generally lower than in the 
us 
weather conditions also have undermined soybean prices the same 
rainy weather that has hampered corn planting in the midwest has 
driven speculation that farmers will switch some of their planned 
corn acres to soybeans since soybeans can be planted later with no 
loss of yield 
mondays forecasts called for relatively little rain this week 
in the midwest 
