<TEXT>
the agriculture department said monday it 
would undertake a more searching look at iraqi credit purchases of 
us farm products including payments above the market price that 
may have provided cash rebates 
officials said an administrative review so far uncovered no 
evidence to suggest that there has been diversion of commodities 
sold to iraq for illegal purposes 
undersecretary richard crowder in releasing a report of the 
review said the us government has not incurred any losses as 
a result of iraqs use of the program 
the departments review involved credit guarantees for up to 
three years the department through its commodity credit corp 
does not lend the money but stands behind commercial banks who do 
iraq has used the guarantees to buy more than 45 billion worth 
of us commodities since 1983 
kelly shipp spokeswoman for agriculture secretary clayton 
yeutter said about 30 million is left in the first 500 million 
worth of guarantees for iraq this fiscal year a decision on the 
second 500 million will be held up while the additional review is 
made 
among the potential irregularities checked by the department was 
a stamp tax of an unspecified amount that iraq had requested of 
some exporters iraq has agreed to exempt the credit shipments in 
the future officials 
the report said the administrative review which included a 
visit to baghdad last month suggested additional inquiry into two 
key areas 
one question involves the extent and reasons for high prices in 
certain transactions including corn rice and sugar during 1985 
to 1987 prices paid by iraq appeared to be at least 10 per metric 
ton higher than typical world prices for rice and corn and 15 to 
40 higher for sugar 
it appears that these price levels may have resulted in part 
from supplier perceptions that iraq was a very highrisk market due 
to wartime conditions with iran the report said 
other possible reasons may have been the limited number of 
us suppliers who were willing to deal in this highrisk market 
when iraq was at war with iran and iraqs policy of seeking 
freight financing which only a few suppliers were able or willing 
to provide 
another uncertainty was the extent of services that may have 
been provided in connection with the credit sales and whether the 
values of those sales were properly reported 
the report said these services requested of exporters by iraq 
appear to have been in the form of either additional agricultural 
products nonagricultural products such as truck parts or tires 
cash rebates or discounts or use of designated iraqi shipping 
companies 
officials said the review began last fall after the department 
learned of allegations that approximately 720 million of 
guaranteed loans were part of a loan portfolio under federal 
investigation in atlanta 
allegedly the cccguaranteed loans were part of a clandestine 
loan operation in which officials of the atlanta branch of the 
banca nazionale del lavoro had booked more than 2 billion in 
unauthorized and unreported loans to iraq the report said 
federal grand jury proceedings in the atlanta case have yet to 
produce indictments and no details are available the report said 
