<TEXT>
sundstrand corp has agreed to abide by 
federal securities laws that regulators said it ignored while 
overbilling the government on defense contracts 
the aerospace contractor although neither admitting nor denying 
charges it violated securities laws agreed to a permanent 
injunction in us district court monday barring it from 
disregarding accounting and financial reporting rules in the future 
sundstrand also agreed to set up a committee of independent 
directors to review whether the companys fraud case led to 
violations not addressed by the securities and exchange commission 
in its complaint 
the settlement subject to approval by a judge would end the 
secs investigation 
sundstrand pleaded guilty in 1988 to overbilling the government 
on defense contracts for airplane parts and paid nearly 200 
million to settle the case the biggest penalty ever assessed for 
defense fraud 
the commission charged that by concealing millions of dollars in 
cost overruns between 1980 and 1986 sundstrand misled investors by 
underestimating its debts and overstating its profits 
sec lawyer wendy d fox said the injunction was necessary to 
ensure sundstrand will comply with security laws in the future 
sundstrand has settled this matter in order to avoid 
protracted and costly litigation over practices long since 
discontinued by this company said harry c stonecipher 
president and chief executive officer 
sundstrand has moved on and the injunction will have no 
financial impact on the company it obliges us to do what we would 
do in any event that is to comply with the law 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

